Product Version     25.10    Cadence Design Systems, Inc.
verifyWellAntenna(25.10)                              verifyWellAntenna(25.10)

Name
       verifyWellAntenna - Checks for any CORE rows that have well-process-an-
       tenna violations

Syntax
       verifyWellAntenna

       [-help]

       [-needToProtect {<cell_list>}]

       [-changeToProtect {<cell_list>}]

       [-changeToNotProtect {<cell_list>}]

       [-report <filename> [-detailed]]

       Checks  for  any  CORE  rows that have well-process-antenna violations.
       Well-process-antenna violations are normally caused by rows with  decap
       cells  that do not have any protecting cells in the same row. This com-
       mand marks with a violation marker any such CORE  cell.  You  can  then
       write  a Tcl script to put in a well-antenna cell next to the violation
       marker.

Parameters
       -help  Prints a brief description that includes the  type  and  default
              information for each verifyWellAntenna parameter.

              For  a  detailed  description of the command and all its parame-
              ters, use the man command:

              man verifyWellAntenna

       -changeToNotProtect {<cell_list>}
              Specifies the cell names that are to be marked as cells that  do
              not  protect rows. By default, the cells with LEF class CORE but
              without a subclass (e.g. normal BUF and AND2 cells) are  assumed
              to  have a well discharge path that protects a row from well-an-
              tenna violations. Use -changeToNotProtect option to override the
              default for any of these cells that do not protect a  row.  Pat-
              tern matching with * is allowed in cell names.

       -changeToProtect {<cell_list>}
              Specifies  the  cell  names  that are to be marked as protection
              cells.  By  default,  cells  with  CLASS  CORE  and  a  subclass
              {FEEDTHRU  |  TIEHIGH | TIELOW | SPACER | ANTENNACELL | WELLTAP}
              or cells with class ENDCAP (with or without any subclass) do not
              have a well-discharge path to protect a row. Use the  -changeTo-
              Protect  option  to  override the default for any of these cells
              that do protect the row. Pattern matching with * is allowed.

       -needToProtect {<cell_list>}
              Specifies the cell names that need protection  (typically  decap
              cells).  This  option also indicates that the specified cells do
              not protect the row they are in. Pattern matching with * is  al-
              lowed in cell names.

       -report <filename>
              Specifies  the report file name. By default, the report includes
              information about only the cells that you specified with the op-
              tions.

       -detailed
              If you specify -detailed,  verifyWellAntenna reports every class
              CORE and  ENDCAP cell with its subclass and protection status to
              the  <filename> report.

Example
       Normally, the decap cells are the only cells that need protection. How-
       ever, if the standard-cell library in your design has one of the ENDCAP
       cells with a well-antenna protection device built-in, and  the  filler,
       well-tap,  tie-high  and  tie-low cells are just class CORE rather than
       with the correct CORE sub-class, you can use the following command:

       verifyWellAntenna -needToProtect decap* -changeToProtect  wellAntEndCap
       -changeToNotProtect {filler* welltap* tie*} -report wellant.rpt

Related Information
       "Verifying  Well-Process-Antenna  Violations"  in  the  Identifying and
       Viewing Violations chapter of User Guide.

